For simplicity, we used the price of the pool at future times as the reference price. This will undercount future price by ignoring price impact and fees paid to LPs, but it is an improvement.

5/ 

Lastly, this query includes the fee given to the LPs as part of the exchange rate. We adjust for this to find the correct execution price.

4/ 

Another issue with this query is that it doesn’t factor price impact into the execution price—instead, it only takes the mid-price at the time the trade was executed. 

Price impact is good for LPs because it means they are selling fewer assets at less favorable prices.

3/

For one, it doesn’t account for LP fees! When we factor in LP fees, we find that ETH/USDC LPs have generated 2.5x more fees for LPs than the value lost via markout.

First, what is ‘markout’? 

In this instance, markout is defined as the difference between the execution price versus the price 24 hours later. 

The logic in this chart is that LPs lose money when they sell an asset that appreciates or buy an asset that depreciates.

odds of successful 1st co = 0.01

if 1st co successful, odds of 2nd co now = 0.1

@PaulRBerg there's a difference between compounding probabilities and probabilities in a vacuum 

e.g. 

odds of flipping heads every time over n flips is 0.5^n 

odds of flipping heads at any given time is always 0.5
